Inflation in Europe jumped for food
The accelerated inflation measured in the euro area is mainly due to the constant rise in food prices.
November price increases in 13 euro area countries were above expectations, with annual inflation of 3.1% registered at 2.6% in October, announced by the Luxembourg Statistical Office of the Union.
The official forecast assumed only 3 percent, provided by Bloomberg.
Unlike the US, British and Canadian emission banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not reduce the basic interest rate, with the reduction leading to an inflation spiral, along with rising raw material prices and declining unemployment.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below two percent, but close to it.
According to one of the analysts, the ECB is in an absurd situation: it must "discourage inflation" so that it does not have to do anything later.
In Germany, November inflation is a 15-year record of 3.3%; in Spain, it rose from 3.6% to 4.1%.
Inflation in the euro area has gone up due to rising food and energy prices.
The term price of wheat has risen by 88 percent, and also the course of soy has reached the highest value since 1973.
Similarly, in 2007, much more had to be paid for edible oil and dairy products.
The price of oil on world markets increased by 52% this year, and last month, a barrel of black gold cost almost $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will jump from 2.1% to 2.5% in 2008, but will fall to 1.9% in 2009.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate over the next 3-4 months will remain approximately 3%, but its average annual rate will be 2.1%.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to reduce interest rates twice during 2008.
