In many places, it saves on disinfectants.
This year, more than a thousand cases of infection, mainly due to inappropriate antibiotic use, were registered in hospitals.
The sanitation conditions of hospitals, overloading beds, overloading the staff is not helping to stop the disease, says the head of the National Epidemiological Center.
In many places it is also saved on disinfectants.
Recently, MRSA infection was diagnosed in the trauma ward of St. John's Hospital.
Antibiotic-resistant bacteria were discovered in a man who entered the hospital after a serious car accident.
The patient was isolated.
A similar infection occurred at the same site at the beginning of the year.
A patient injured in a serious car accident was released home, but not long after that he had to return with an MRSA infection and due to a bacterium found in his body one major operation could not yet be performed.
By 10 December this year, 1 094 hospital infections caused by multi-resistant disease agents were reported to the Nesocomialis Surveillance National System, Karolina Böröcz, the primary of the National Epidemiological Centre.
This means that so many infections caused by multi-resistant disease agents have been registered with certainty in hospitals, others are not known.
Almost two thirds (683) of the infections were caused by MRSA, or methicillin-oxacillin-resistant staph.
Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria are carried by a third of the people in the nose without causing the disease.
Infections caused by SA (e. g. cervical inflammation, almond inflammation, skin infection, early infection) respond well to antibiotics and can be treated well.
However, if antibiotics are administered to an exaggerated or inappropriate extent, they will develop from a bacteria that responds well to antibiotics, which is highly resistant to antibiotics and which spreads rapidly under inadequate hospital conditions.
Especially in the case of temporary or permanent malfunctioning of the immune system in patients with weakened body weight, low body weight, or in patients over the years, it may cause serious hospital infections such as early infection or sepsis.
According to the Chief Medical Officer of St. John's Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, such infections are part of daily practice in hospitals.
"Infection must not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is not only there," said Tibor Nyulasi, "where the presence of the disease agent is not investigated."
He resists antibiotics.
"We isolate these patients, the attending staff treats them in rubber gloves and mask and we have the necessary antibiotics to treat them," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients admitted to the hospital are first examined if they are present in their MRSA but this is not always possible to avoid infection.
Sampling is not in fashion
The majority of hospital infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but the current conditions and conditions in domestic hospitals are not favourable to preventing and spreading multi-resistant disease agents, Karolina Böröcz claims.
As this infection is well known in hospitals and homes for elderly people, hospitals receiving patients should be checked and MRSA carriers immediately isolated.
However, the collection of microbiological samples in Hungarian hospitals is not in fashion.
This also involves the fact that the National Health Insurance Fund does not fund these examinations.
Most cases are thus revealed, if the patient suffers from an observable MRSA infection, said the mayor of the epidemiological centre.
The European Union has strict recommendations for appropriate treatment of antibiotics in the field of human medicine, and there are also domestic guidelines for treating individual infections, diseases.
There is a need to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, or that microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but even hospitals do not comply in all cases.
Microbiological samples are even more rare in the primary and outpatient treatment of patients, said Karolina Böröcz.
Save on disinfectants
According to scientific evidence, MRSA is most commonly disseminated to patients through medical personnel.
This is why hand washing and gloves and masks play a very important role, but there are also serious shortcomings in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted by drip infection and touch, but it is not always possible to isolate infected patients under the conditions of domestic hospitals.
On the contrary, the rooms are often crowded, the beds are often very close together, although from an epidemiological point of view patients should be at least 1.5 metres away.
As Karolina Böröcz pointed out, unfortunately, we can also see that hospitals that are in an unfavourable material situation are being spared on disinfectants, there are few nurses and patients, thus increasing the chances of infection.
According to Karolina Böröcz, where the necessary protective measures are followed, similar infections can be shown to be less or the further spread of the disease agent can be stopped.
Government programme against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for health insurance companies, which is why it is being fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has drawn up a programme for the prevention of MRSA, or a reduction in its occurrence.
The programme appears to be successful, according to published data, MRSA infections in England show a declining trend.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) ranks among its priorities the prevention of the emergence of multi-resisting disease agents (including MRSA) or hospital infections caused by these disease agents.
