Political Capital: The Hungarian Guard has increased the country's risk
The activities of the Hungarian Guard, founded with the support of the Jobbik Magyarország movement in August of this year, according to the Risk Analysis Division of the Political Capital Institute, increased the political risk of Hungary and the entire region in several respects.
The "risk warning 'developed by the company states that, in the context of the Hungarian Guard's activities, the greatest political risk is that" violent ethnic conflicts can occur in the short term by sharpening the already existing ethnic tensions between the Roma and the non-Roma population of Hungary'.
The main reason is that the Hungarian Guard's political strategy is likely to be aimed at provoking such an event - adds a research institute.
As he writes, all of this can be explained by one of the greatest negligence of Hungarian political leaders: "public debate on the Roma issue was left to representatives of radical and extremist political groups who could build a political strategy on the Roma-Hungarian conflict."
This deepens the problem, makes normal dialogue impossible, reinforces extremists and increases the likelihood of violent conflicts - the Institute is judging.
In addition, according to the Research Institute, the Hungarian Guard's work, due to the great attention of domestic and foreign media, "has largely ruined Hungary's image abroad, particularly in terms of the country's faith in stability and its democratic maturity."
The Institute recalls: a part of the reorganisation of Hungarian radical and ultra-right groups, which since autumn 2006 have been getting more and more publicity and leadership, is that several organizations have been created in Hungary since the summer of 2007, which are themselves called "national militia" associations.
"A common feature of these groupings is that they define themselves as civil associations, while openly proclaiming - and also armed - their members' readiness to perform defence tasks (in the event of natural disasters, country attacks, disturbance of order), in addition to pointing out the inability of the police, the army, or the state," he adds.
It also notes: this is all happening in a way that seeks to pack up all sorts of political efforts built on the resistance of society to politics and parties to civil clothing.
Therefore, the emphasis on civil status and the form of the association is not merely to avoid the legal difficulties of the judicial registration, but is also a political strategy in the case of these groups.
According to the analysis, the Hungarian Guard is also a risk-enhancing factor from the point of view of neighbourly relations.
"In recent months, they have pointed to the Hungarian Guard in several neighbouring countries as a potential source of danger, with ultra-nationalist political leaders of some neighbouring countries calling for the creation of the Hungarian Guard to excuse their own anti-Hungarian policy.
All this may affect the political stability of the region, "he adds.
According to the Research Institute, the creation of the Hungarian Guard in Central and Eastern Europe is not an isolated phenomenon, so the political risks for the region as a whole have increased.
As it writes, the Hungarian Guard's activities are similar, for example, to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, the creation of which was announced in August 2007 by the ultra-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
