Holidays aren't open everywhere.
In Hungary, the days of leave are precisely laid down by law, and it has become a general practice that working days are being moved around the holidays, which we will expect less in the next year.
In the European Union and in America, the holidays are not uniform.
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between national and national holidays and working days.
The days of work are usually linked to church holidays or important historical events.
We also celebrate New Year's Eve: the last day of the old year and the first day of the new year is work leave - for New Year's Eve so that people can relax after New Year's Eve.
In the course of the year, we have a total of eleven free holidays.
The national holiday is 15th March celebrating the revolution of 1848 and 23rd October, the commemorative day of the revolution of 1956.
On August 20th we celebrate the founding of the state, 1 May work, 1 and 2 November we remember deceased relatives and friends.
Besides, we have two-day holidays Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
Since our national, national or religious holidays are rarely for the weekend according to the calendar, it has become a practice to move a working day in cases where we only work one day before or after the holiday.
The price for extended weekends, however, is that we remain in the workplace and school on the previous Saturdays.
When the day immediately preceding or following the holiday is worked out, it has been regulated by the Minister of Labour for many years in a special decree.
The legislation applies equally to all employers and workers employed by them, to public employees and to persons in the public service.
It does not, however, concern companies and institutions which are operating without interruption or with regard to their destination operating even on working days.
This year, the conditions of employment will be changed only around the end of the year: from 24 December, life in the country will almost stop, because according to experience, most people will "make up" the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve or take advantage of the vacation they have saved.
In the next year, several of our holidays fall into the middle, or at the end of the week, so the shift of the working day will be less than this year.
For the first time, the calendar changes around the holiday work so that workers can stay home for four days straight.
On 26 April, Saturday will be a working day, so that Friday may be a day of rest on 2 May.
The next transfer is related to the holiday of October 23: on Saturday, October 18, work will take place instead of Friday 24.
The end of the year, however, will be able to take place entirely in the name of the holidays, because from 24 December they will have almost 24-hour holidays, even though New Year's Eve is the center.
