The banks want to solve the crisis
The US Federal Reserve, the European Central Bank and the central banks of Britain, Switzerland and Canada have decided to fight the financial market crisis together.
This will bring more than $100 billion into the currency markets through auctions.
In these auctions, the bank is auctioning the interest rate for which they are willing to borrow money.
For example, the US Fed sends $40 billion to the auction, making the European and Swiss central banks available another 24 billion.
This is the first time that national central banks have agreed to a coordinated action to prevent or reduce the consequences of the financial crisis following the attacks of the 11th September.
"This move is intended to address the economy's biggest difficulties, the growing lack of free capital that banks could lend," Bernard Baumoc, from the economic Outlook Group, wrote to his clients in his report.
"The coordinated central bank action has reduced the likelihood of a recession in the United States from 65% to 50%," said Baumol in his report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion to outstanding loans, especially in the United States.
Analysts expect further billion losses.
"Central banks must be really worried about what else might follow when they decided to do so," said the chief economist ABN Amro Kieran Davies.
"The situation seems really bad," he added.
Central banks fear that if banks themselves have difficult access to loans, they will also lend credit to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and send the US economy into recession with potential effects on economic growth throughout the world.
The central banks have thus decided, after failing to reduce the so-called LIBOR rate, the London interbank rate used to lend money on the interbank market.
This meant that banks were still concerned about borrowing money from each other, even though the US, Canada, and Britain central banks reduced their interest rates several times during the autumn.
"It will have the same effect as another fall in interest rates," said Reuters Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting.
Some analysts do not believe that central bank action will contribute to ending the crisis because it does not solve the underlying problem, and that is the fall of the US real estate market.
