Loaded memory
After more than 60 years in a confidential regime, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which depict the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are opening up to the public.
The 47 million archive documents stored in Bad Arolsen (Hesse) were only accessible for "humanitarian" purposes, i.e. individually and by name, at the request of the former victim or his authorised persons.
Eleven states in charge of managing archives - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May to open them to scientists and historians.
Since the process of ratifying this agreement by all states is over, the opening took effect yesterday.
Sensitive information
The free access of historians to Bad Arolsen will enable us to explore "particularly the movements of prisoners, the population of camps and the state of health of forced workers," explains Reto Meistern, director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (CICR).
Until recently, several states, among them Germany, were against making these nominal documents available to the public because of the sensitive nature of some information.
What is supposed to be homosexuality or mental disability of some of the victims of deportation.
The registers of concentration camps or warrants drawn up by the Gestapo were collected after the war for practical purposes to find deported or forced work by civilians, to bring them proof of their internment in order to open the way for their compensation.
Today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen are dealing with tens of thousands of individual requests.
However, for a part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen represents only a limited benefit.
"Nothing fundamentally new can be expected from these papers," said Prof. Wolfgang Benz, Director of the Centre for the Study of Anti-Semitism of Berlin Technische Universität.
