Congress has approved the transposition of MiFID in force since November 1
In parallel with the parliamentary negotiations that were concluded today by the vote of Congress on the amendments incorporated by the Senate into the bill, the government submitted a public hearing to a regulation that is developing a new law in order for both of them to enter into force before the end of the year.
The representatives of each party have consistently highlighted the efforts of Members and Senators to negotiate and agree the best standard in order to guarantee investor protection and the detailed regulation of the activities of operators needed for the effective functioning of the markets.
The MiFID Directive, which regulates the Securities Trading Act, envisages the modernisation of financial markets while strengthening investor protection, improving the supervisory powers of the State Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between the various supervisory bodies of the European Union.
This new regulation will enable financial consultancy services to be provided to both specialised firms and natural or legal persons and create a new type of financial services (ESIS) companies, financial consultancy companies (AFI) which join securities companies, securities intermediation agencies and portfolio management companies.
In addition, the number of systems for the execution of operations in financial instruments is extended by joining regulated secondary markets with multilateral trading and internalisation systems to compete with current stock brokers.
The Act also obliges firms providing investment services to disseminate on the market information on key aspects of their business profile, exposure to risk and methods of dealing with risk, and requires a statement of all operations undertaken to simplify supervision by CNMV.
During the negotiations with the Congress Trade Commission, several adjustments were included, which excelled in making securitised claims considered a "complex" financial instrument due to the high risk to the investor, which was demonstrated by what happened in the US with high-risk mortgage debt (subprime).
In addition, the transposition of the directive was used to set out the legal functions that the Bachelors in Economics and Corporate Management may hold for 30 years after the Royal Decree, which sets out professional functions reserved for economists, was approved in 1977.
At the same time, the Senate has included the creation of new professions in the financial sector, such as an intermediary that will work externally, will not require permission from CNMV and will be able to provide product trading and customer acquisition services for various investment firms at the same time.
