Concerns about a new gas fight between Russia and Ukraine
There is a dispute over gas prices between Russia and Ukraine, thus increasing the risk that Russian supplies of this fuel to Western Europe may be affected.
The majority of Russian fuel exported to the European Union (EU) is driven by a pipeline through Ukraine, and any dispute between these two countries is closely monitored.
Kiev warned that if Moscow raises Ukraine's gas prices, it would charge Russia higher transit fees.
The previous dispute between the two last year reduced supplies to EU states.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state-owned gas monopoly, Gazprom, are trying to agree on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian gas in 2008.
Gazprom says he will have to charge Ukraine more because he agreed to pay up to 50% more for the gas he receives from neighbouring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say that this could mean that Ukraine will have to pay 40% more for its supplies from Gazprom.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states during the negotiations," said Reuters Ukrainian Minister of Economy Anatoly Kinach.
"The changes in gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the level of transit fees (to Western Europe) via Ukraine."
The last major dispute between Moscow and Kiev caused a reduction in supplies from Gazprom to Ukraine in January 2006.
This caused a devastating fall in exports to Western Europe, which sharply increased prices.
Russian gas represents one quarter of the supply to the European Union.
Russia has the largest gas reserves in the world, but a large part of it remains underutilized.
As a result, Gazprom complements its own gas supply from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet Central Asian republics.
