The climate of Venus is perhaps a view of the future of the Earth.
Scientists announced yesterday that Venus could once have been a pleasant place to live.
The data from an orbiting European station shows that the planet is even more similar to the wilful twin Earth than previously thought.
Venus is the nearest planetary neighbour to Earth.
These two worlds are roughly the same size and orbit along similar paths, but Venus is a little closer to the Sun.
Scientists now believe that billions of years ago, Venus had conditions similar to those on Earth and could be habitable.
But the fueled greenhouse effect caused by carbon dioxide, atmospheric erosion of solar radiation and lower rate of rotation sent Venus along a completely different path of development.
Today, the planet is without water, the temperature on the surface is hot enough to melt lead, and it's ravaged by storms and hurricane winds.
The findings from the European Space Agency Venus Express, which studied the planet for one year, offer a modest insight into how the Earth could develop in the event of catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor of the Oxford University of Physics Department and one of the heads of the Venus Express mission said, "It is becoming increasingly clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that on Earth, even though the planets themselves are otherwise quite similar.
"Our new data allows us to compile a scenario in which Venus began just like the Earth, perhaps even with a habitable environment, billions of years ago."
