Does the sub-prime mortgage crisis affect the US credit card market?
When there's blood in the water, naturally, dorsal fins start to move around.
Now that the US real estate market is fading, predators have focused on the credit card market there.
Goldman Sachs' analysts say that credit card losses could reach $99 billion if subprime mortgages were infested.
The signs of tension are clear.
There are increasing number of incapacity to pay (with more than 30 days delay) and debited accounts (accounts that the provider considers unenforceable).
Last month, HSBC announced that it had lost $1.4 billion in the US consumer credit market - also due to insolvent credit card loans.
But it's too early to panic.
The debited accounts and the inability to repay are still few.
According to Moody's rating agency, 3,89% of the insolvency rate in the third quarter was almost a full percentage point below the average.
The deteriorating rates can be partly explained by technical reasons.
The change in America's 2005 bankruptcy laws has led to a sharp decline in the number of reported credit card losses, which make much of the credit card losses; the number of reports (and thus the number of write-offs) would therefore increase regardless of whether the general conditions for borrowers have deteriorated.
The sector also shows a good rate of maturity, which shows how much consumers pay off their debts per month.
And trust in credit card securities is solid, despite paralysis in other corners of structured finance.
Mr Dennis Moroney of the TowerGroup research firm predicts that their 2007 emissions will be 25% larger than last year.
Direct routes to spread the infection between the sub-prime crisis and the credit card market certainly exist: when loans for real estate assets run dry, consumers are more likely to be owed credit cards.
Credit card publishers, however, look at the cash flow rather than the value of the guarantee items, so falling home prices do not necessarily mean changing the credibility of borrowers.
They may even be advantageous to loan providers.
Consumer incentives to pay off mortgages fall when the value of their assets falls below the value of the loan; as a result, the debt on cards is moved up to the priority list for repayment.
Card publishers can also respond more quickly and flexibly to more turbulent conditions than mortgage providers by changing interest rates or debt limits.
This should, in theory, reduce the risks of a rapid change in the price of guarantee items.
"It will not happen that one beautiful morning we will just review all the loans," says Gary Perlin, financial manager of Capital One.
Even though the risk of subprime mortgage-style explosions is low, the risk of gradual weakening is far more realistic.
If lower home prices and debt cuts push America into recession, the credit card sector will face a darker future.
Watch out for those dorsal fins.
